# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: essential-amino-acid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:essential-amino-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] In the glycolytic pathway, 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate is dephosphorylated to form 3-phosphoglyceric acid in a coupled reaction producing two ATP via substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:essential-amino-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] The single phosphate group left on the 3-PGA molecule then moves from an end carbon to a central carbon, producing 2-phosphoglycerate.
[src:essential-amino-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] This phosphate group relocation is catalyzed by phosphoglycerate mutase, an enzyme that also catalyzes the reverse reaction.
[src:essential-amino-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] Compound C00236 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:essential-amino-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] Enzyme 2.7.2.3 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:essential-amino-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] Compound C00197 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:essential-amino-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] Enzyme 5.4.2.1 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:essential-amino-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] Compound C00631 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:essential-amino-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] In the light-independent reactions (also known as the Calvin-Benson cycle), two 3-phosphoglycerate molecules are synthesized.
[src:essential-amino-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] RuBP, a 5-carbon sugar, undergoes carbon fixation, catalyzed by the rubisco enzyme, to become an unstable 6-carbon intermediate.
[src:essential-amino-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] This intermediate is then cleaved into two, separate 3-carbon molecules of 3-PGA.
[src:essential-amino-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] G3P eventually reacts to form the sugars such as glucose or fructose or more complex starches.
[src:essential-amino-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] Glycerate 3-phosphate (formed from 3-phosphoglycerate) is also a precursor for serine, which, in turn, can create cysteine and glycine through the homocysteine cycle.
[src:essential-amino-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] 3-phosphoglycerate can be separated and measured using paper chromatography as well as with column chromatography and other chromatographic separation methods.
[src:essential-amino-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] It can be identified using both gas-chromatography and liquid-chromatography mass spectrometry and has been optimized for evaluation using tandem MS techniques.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:essential-amino-acid/acid] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:essential-amino-acid/alanine] Under biological conditions, alanine exists in its zwitterionic form with its amine group protonated (as −NH+3) and its carboxyl group deprotonated (as −CO−2).
[src:essential-amino-acid/alanine] Alanine is encoded by all codons starting with GC (GCU, GCC, GCA, and GCG).
[src:essential-amino-acid/alanine] The L-isomer of alanine (left-handed) is the one that is incorporated into proteins.
[src:essential-amino-acid/alanine] L-alanine is second only to L-leucine in rate of occurrence, accounting for 7.8% of the primary structure in a sample of 1,150 proteins.
[src:essential-amino-acid/alanine] The right-handed form, D-alanine, occurs in peptides in some bacterial cell walls (in peptidoglycan) and in some peptide antibiotics, and occurs in the tissues of many crustaceans and molluscs as an osmolyte.
[src:essential-amino-acid/alanine] Alanine is not an essential amino acid in humans because it can be synthesized metabolically and does not need to be present in the diet.
[src:essential-amino-acid/alanine] However hypoalaninemia (alanine deficiency) is possible under certain conditions such as ketotic hypoglycemia.
[src:essential-amino-acid/alanine] Alanine was first synthesized in 1850 when Adolph Strecker combined acetaldehyde and ammonia with hydrogen cyanide.
[src:essential-amino-acid/alanine] The amino acid was named *Alanin* in German, in reference to aldehyde, with the interfix *-an-* for ease of pronunciation, the German ending *-in* used in chemical compounds being analogous to English *-ine*.
[src:essential-amino-acid/alanine] Alanine is an aliphatic amino acid, because the side-chain connected to the α-carbon atom is a methyl group (-CH3).
[src:essential-amino-acid/alanine] Alanine is the simplest α-amino acid after glycine.
[src:essential-amino-acid/alanine] The methyl side-chain of alanine is non-reactive and is therefore hardly ever directly involved in protein function.
[src:essential-amino-acid/alanine] Alanine is a nonessential amino acid, meaning it can be manufactured by the human body, and does not need to be obtained through the diet.
[src:essential-amino-acid/alanine] Alanine is found in a wide variety of foods, but is particularly concentrated in meats.
[src:essential-amino-acid/aliphatic-compound] In organic chemistry, hydrocarbons (compounds composed solely of carbon and hydrogen) are divided into two classes: aromatic compounds and **aliphatic compounds** (/ˌælɪˈfætɪk/; G.
[src:essential-amino-acid/aliphatic-compound] Aliphatic compounds can be saturated (in which all the C-C bonds are single, requiring the structure to be completed, or 'saturated', by hydrogen) like hexane, or unsaturated, like hexene and hexyne.
[src:essential-amino-acid/aliphatic-compound] Open-chain compounds, whether straight or branched, and which contain no rings of any type, are always aliphatic.
[src:essential-amino-acid/aliphatic-compound] Cyclic compounds can be aliphatic if they are not aromatic.
[src:essential-amino-acid/aliphatic-compound] Aliphatic compounds can be saturated, joined by single bonds (alkanes), or unsaturated, with double bonds (alkenes) or triple bonds (alkynes).
[src:essential-amino-acid/aliphatic-compound] If other elements (heteroatoms) are bound to the carbon chain, the most common being oxygen, nitrogen, sulfur, and chlorine, it is no longer a hydrocarbon, and therefore no longer an aliphatic compound.
[src:essential-amino-acid/aliphatic-compound] However, such compounds may still be referred to as aliphatic if the hydrocarbon portion of the molecule is aliphatic, e.g. aliphatic amines, to differentiate them from aromatic amines.
[src:essential-amino-acid/aliphatic-compound] The least complex aliphatic compound is methane (CH4).
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids can be classified according to the locations of the core structural functional groups (alpha- (α-), beta- (β-), gamma- (γ-) amino acids, etc.); other categories relate to polarity, ionization, and side-chain group type (aliphatic, acyclic, aromatic, polar, etc.).
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In the form of proteins, amino-acid *residues* form the second-largest component (water being the largest) of human muscles and other tissues.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Beyond their role as residues in proteins, amino acids participate in a number of processes such as neurotransmitter transport and biosynthesis.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] It is thought that they played a key role in enabling life on Earth and its emergence.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are formally named by the IUPAC-IUBMB Joint Commission on Biochemical Nomenclature in terms of the fictitious "neutral" structure shown in the illustration.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, the systematic name of alanine is 2-aminopropanoic acid, based on the formula CH3−CH(NH2)−COOH.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The first few amino acids were discovered in the early 1800s.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In 1806, French chemists Louis-Nicolas Vauquelin and Pierre Jean Robiquet isolated a compound from asparagus that was subsequently named asparagine, the first amino acid to be discovered.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Cystine was discovered in 1810, although its monomer, cysteine, remained undiscovered until 1884.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Glycine and leucine were discovered in 1820.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The last of the 20 common amino acids to be discovered was threonine in 1935 by William Cumming Rose, who also determined the essential amino acids and established the minimum daily requirements of all amino acids for optimal growth.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The unity of the chemical category was recognized by Wurtz in 1865, but he gave no particular name to it.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The first use of the term "amino acid" in the English language dates from 1898, while the German term, *Aminosäure*, was used earlier.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Proteins were found to yield amino acids after enzymatic digestion or acid hydrolysis.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In 1902, Emil Fischer and Franz Hofmeister independently proposed that proteins are formed from many amino acids, whereby bonds are formed between the amino group of one amino acid with the carboxyl group of another, resulting in a linear structure that Fischer termed "peptide".
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] 2-, alpha-, or α-amino acids have the generic formula H2NCHRCOOH in most cases, where R is an organic substituent known as a "side chain".
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Of the many hundreds of described amino acids, 22 are proteinogenic ("protein-building").
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] It is these 22 compounds that combine to give a vast array of peptides and proteins assembled by ribosomes.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids may arise through nonribosomal peptide synthesis.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Modified amino acids, by contrast, typically result from post-translational modification.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CO−2, such as β-alanine, a component of carnosine and a few other peptides, are β-amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Ones with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CXY−CO−2 are γ-amino acids, and so on, where X and Y are two substituents (one of which is normally H).
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The carbon atom next to the carboxyl group is called the α–carbon.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In proteinogenic amino acids, it bears the amine and the R group or side chain specific to each amino acid, as well as a hydrogen atom.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] With the exception of glycine, for which the side chain is also a hydrogen atom, the α–carbon is stereogenic.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] All chiral proteinogenic amino acids have the L configuration.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] They are "left-handed" enantiomers, which refers to the stereoisomers of the alpha carbon.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] A few D-amino acids ("right-handed") have been found in nature, e.g., in bacterial envelopes, as a neuromodulator (D-serine), and in some antibiotics.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Rarely, D-amino acid residues are found in proteins, and are converted from the L-amino acid as a post-translational modification.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Five amino acids possess a charge at neutral pH.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Often these side chains appear at the surfaces on proteins to enable their solubility in water, and side chains with opposite charges form important electrostatic contacts called salt bridges that maintain structures within a single protein or between interfacing proteins.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Many proteins bind metal into their structures specifically, and these interactions are commonly mediated by charged side chains such as aspartate, glutamate and histidine.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Under certain conditions, each ion-forming group can be charged, forming double salts.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The two negatively charged amino acids at neutral pH are aspartate (Asp, D) and glutamate (Glu, E).
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The anionic carboxylate groups behave as Brønsted bases in most circumstances.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Enzymes in very low pH environments, like the aspartic protease pepsin in mammalian stomachs, may have catalytic aspartate or glutamate residues that act as Brønsted acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] There are three amino acids with side chains that are cations at neutral pH: arginine (Arg, R), lysine (Lys, K) and histidine (His, H).
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Arginine has a charged guanidino group and lysine a charged alkyl amino group, and are fully protonated at pH 7.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Histidine's imidazole group has a pKa of 6.0, and is only around 10% protonated at neutral pH.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Because histidine is easily found in its basic and conjugate acid forms it often participates in catalytic proton transfers in enzyme reactions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The polar, uncharged amino acids serine (Ser, S), threonine (Thr, T), asparagine (Asn, N) and glutamine (Gln, Q) readily form hydrogen bonds with water and other amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] They do not ionize in normal conditions, a prominent exception being the catalytic serine in serine proteases.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] This is an example of severe perturbation, and is not characteristic of serine residues in general.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Threonine has two chiral centers, not only the L (2*S*) chiral center at the α-carbon shared by all amino acids apart from achiral glycine, but also (3*R*) at the β-carbon.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The full stereochemical specification is (2*S*,3*R*)-L-threonine.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Because of the presence of phenolic hydroxyl group with a pKa = ~10, tyrosine is best classified as a neutral polar amino acid, but with amphipathic character that makes it less polar than classical small polar amino acid residues.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Nonpolar amino acid interactions are the primary driving force behind the processes that fold proteins into their functional three dimensional structures.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] None of these amino acids' side chains ionize easily, and therefore do not have pKas.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Several side chains are not described well by the charged, polar and hydrophobic categories.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Glycine (Gly, G) could be considered a polar amino acid since its small size means that its solubility is largely determined by the amino and carboxylate groups.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] However, the lack of any side chain provides glycine with a unique flexibility among amino acids with large ramifications to protein folding.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Cysteine (Cys, C) can also form hydrogen bonds readily, which would place it in the polar amino acid category, though it can often be found in protein structures forming covalent bonds, called disulphide bonds, with other cysteines.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] These bonds influence the folding and stability of proteins, and are essential in the formation of antibodies.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Proline (Pro, P) has an alkyl side chain and could be considered hydrophobic, but because the side chain joins back onto the alpha amino group it becomes particularly inflexible when incorporated into proteins.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Similar to glycine this influences protein structure in a way unique among amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Selenocysteine (Sec, U) is a rare amino acid not directly encoded by DNA, but is incorporated into proteins via the ribosome.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Selenocysteine has a lower redox potential compared to the similar cysteine, and participates in several unique enzymatic reactions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine (Pyl, O) is another amino acid not encoded in DNA, but synthesized into protein by ribosomes.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] It is found in archaeal species where it participates in the catalytic activity of several methyltransferases.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The 20 canonical amino acids can be classified according to their properties.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Important factors are charge, hydrophilicity or hydrophobicity, size, and functional groups.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] These properties influence protein structure and protein–protein interactions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The water-soluble proteins tend to have their hydrophobic residues (Leu, Ile, Val, Phe, and Trp) buried in the middle of the protein, whereas hydrophilic side chains are exposed to the aqueous solvent.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] (In biochemistry, a residue refers to a specific monomer *within* the polymeric chain of a polysaccharide, protein or nucleic acid.) The integral membrane proteins tend to have outer rings of exposed hydrophobic amino acids that anchor them in the lipid bilayer.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Some peripheral membrane proteins have a patch of hydrophobic amino acids on their surface that sticks to the membrane.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In a similar fashion, proteins that have to bind to positively charged molecules have surfaces rich in negatively charged amino acids such as glutamate and aspartate, while proteins binding to negatively charged molecules have surfaces rich in positively charged amino acids like lysine and arginine.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, lysine and arginine are present in large amounts in the low-complexity regions of nucleic-acid binding proteins.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] There are various hydrophobicity scales of amino acid residues.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Some amino acids have special properties.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Cysteine can form covalent disulfide bonds to other cysteine residues.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Proline forms a cycle to the polypeptide backbone, and glycine is more flexible than other amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Glycine and proline are strongly present within low complexity regions of both eukaryotic and prokaryotic proteins, whereas the opposite is the case with cysteine, phenylalanine, tryptophan, methionine, valine, leucine, isoleucine, which are highly reactive, or complex, or hydrophobic.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, a signaling protein can attach and then detach from a cell membrane, because it contains cysteine residues that can have the fatty acid palmitic acid added to them and subsequently removed.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The common natural forms of amino acids have a zwitterionic structure, with −NH+3 (−NH+2− in the case of proline) and −CO−2 functional groups attached to the same C atom, and are thus α-amino acids, and are the only ones found in proteins during translation in the ribosome.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In aqueous solution at pH close to neutrality, amino acids are energetically favored in their zwitterionic form, with a deprotonated CO−2 group and a protonated NH+3 group, because the high dielectric constant of water and its hydrogen-bonding network effectively stabilize separated charges.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Thus, the overall structure is NH+3−CHR−CO−2, and the so-called "neutral forms" −NH2−CHR−CO2H are not present to any measurable degree at physiological pH.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In strongly acidic conditions (pH below 3), the carboxylate group becomes protonated and the structure becomes an ammonio carboxylic acid, NH+3−CHR−CO2H.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] This is relevant for enzymes like pepsin that are active in acidic environments such as the mammalian stomach and lysosomes, but does not significantly apply to intracellular enzymes.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In highly basic conditions (pH greater than 10, not normally seen in physiological conditions), the ammonio group is deprotonated to give NH2−CHR−CO−2.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Although various definitions of acids and bases are used in chemistry, the only one that is useful for chemistry in aqueous solution is that of Brønsted: an acid is a species that can donate a proton to another species, and a base is one that can accept a proton.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] This criterion is used to label the groups in the above illustration.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The carboxylate side chains of aspartate and glutamate residues are the principal Brønsted bases in proteins.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Likewise, lysine, tyrosine and cysteine will typically act as a Brønsted acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Histidine under these conditions can act both as a Brønsted acid and a base.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] For amino acids with uncharged side-chains the zwitterion predominates at pH values between the two p*K*a values, but coexists in equilibrium with small amounts of net negative and net positive ions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] At the midpoint between the two p*K*a values, the trace amount of net negative and trace of net positive ions balance, so that average net charge of all forms present is zero.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] This pH is known as the isoelectric point p*I*, so p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a2).
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] For amino acids with charged side chains, the p*K*a of the side chain is involved.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Thus for aspartate or glutamate with negative side chains, the terminal amino group is essentially entirely in the charged form −NH+3, but this positive charge needs to be balanced by the state with just one C-terminal carboxylate group is negatively charged.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] This occurs halfway between the two carboxylate p*K*a values: p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a(R)), where p*K*a(R) is the side chain p*K*a.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Similar considerations apply to other amino acids with ionizable side-chains, including not only glutamate (similar to aspartate), but also cysteine, histidine, lysine, tyrosine and arginine with positive side chains.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids have zero mobility in electrophoresis at their isoelectric point, although this behaviour is more usually exploited for peptides and proteins than single amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Zwitterionic amino acids exhibit minimal solubility at their isoelectric point, and in some cases can be isolated from aqueous solution by adjusting the pH to the appropriate isoelectric value.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Although one-letter symbols are included in the table, IUPAC–IUBMB recommend that "Use of the one-letter symbols should be restricted to the comparison of long sequences".
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In addition to the specific amino acid codes, placeholders are used in cases where chemical or crystallographic analysis of a peptide or protein cannot conclusively determine the identity of a residue.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] They are also used to summarize conserved protein sequence motifs.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The use of single letters to indicate sets of similar residues is similar to the use of abbreviation codes for degenerate bases.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In addition, many nonstandard amino acids have a specific code.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, several peptide drugs, such as Bortezomib and MG132, are artificially synthesized and retain their protecting groups, which have specific codes.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Bortezomib is Pyz–Phe–boroLeu, and MG132 is Z–Leu–Leu–Leu–al.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] To aid in the analysis of protein structure, photo-reactive amino acid analogs are available.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] These include photoleucine (**pLeu**) and photomethionine (**pMet**).
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are the precursors to proteins.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] They join by condensation reactions to form short polymer chains called peptides or longer chains called either polypeptides or proteins.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] These chains are linear and unbranched, with each amino acid residue within the chain attached to two neighboring amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In nature, the process of making proteins encoded by RNA genetic material is called *translation* and involves the step-by-step addition of amino acids to a growing protein chain by a ribozyme that is called a ribosome.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The order in which the amino acids are added is read through the genetic code from an mRNA template, which is an RNA derived from one of the organism's genes.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] There are 22 amino acids that get naturally incorporated into polypeptides; these are called *proteinogenic amino acids* or *natural amino acids*.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Of these, 20 are encoded by the universal genetic code.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The remaining 2, selenocysteine and pyrrolysine, are incorporated into proteins by unique synthetic mechanisms.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Selenocysteine is incorporated when the mRNA being translated includes a SECIS element, which causes the UGA codon to encode selenocysteine instead of a stop codon.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine is used by some methanogenic archaea in enzymes that they use to produce methane.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] It is coded for with the codon UAG, which is normally a stop codon in other organisms.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The 20 amino acids that are encoded directly by the codons of the universal genetic code are called *standard* or *canonical* amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] A modified form of methionine (*N*-formylmethionine) is often incorporated in place of methionine as the initial amino acid of proteins in bacteria, mitochondria and plastids (including chloroplasts).
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Other amino acids are called *nonstandard* or *non-canonical*.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Most of the nonstandard amino acids are also non-proteinogenic (i.e. they cannot be incorporated into proteins during translation), but two of them are proteinogenic, as they can be incorporated translationally into proteins by exploiting information not encoded in the universal genetic code.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The two nonstandard proteinogenic amino acids are selenocysteine (present in many non-eukaryotes as well as most eukaryotes, but not coded directly by DNA) and pyrrolysine (found only in some archaea and at least one bacterium).
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The incorporation of these nonstandard amino acids is rare.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, 25 human proteins include selenocysteine in their primary structure, and the structurally characterized enzymes (selenoenzymes) employ selenocysteine as the catalytic moiety in their active sites.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine and selenocysteine are encoded via variant codons.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, selenocysteine is encoded by stop codon and SECIS element.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Aside from the 22 proteinogenic amino acids, many *non-proteinogenic* amino acids are known.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] These either are not found in proteins (for example carnitine, GABA, ornithine) or are not produced directly and in isolation by standard cellular machinery.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, hydroxyproline is synthesized from proline, and selenomethionine is produced by metabolic modification of methionine.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids that are found in proteins are formed by post-translational modification.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Such modifications can also determine the localization of the protein, e.g., the addition of long hydrophobic groups can cause a protein to bind to a phospholipid membrane.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Some non-proteinogenic amino acids are not found in proteins.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Examples include 2-aminoisobutyric acid and the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids often occur as intermediates in the metabolic pathways for standard amino acids – for example, ornithine and citrulline occur in the urea cycle, part of amino acid catabolism (see below).
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] A rare exception to the dominance of α-amino acids in biology is the β-amino acid beta alanine (3-aminopropanoic acid), which is used in plants and microorganisms in the synthesis of pantothenic acid (vitamin B5), a component of coenzyme A.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Many proteinogenic and non-proteinogenic amino acids have biological functions beyond being precursors to proteins and peptides.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In humans, amino acids also have important roles in diverse biosynthetic pathways.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Defenses against herbivores in plants sometimes employ amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] However, not all of the functions of other abundant nonstandard amino acids are known.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Animals ingest amino acids in the form of protein.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The protein is broken down into its constituent amino acids in the process of digestion.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The amino acids are then used to synthesize new proteins and other nitrogenous biomolecules, or they are further catabolized through oxidation to provide a source of energy.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The oxidation pathway starts with the removal of the amino group by a transaminase; the amino group is then fed into the urea cycle.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The other product of transamidation is a keto acid that enters the citric acid cycle.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Glucogenic amino acids can also be converted into glucose, through gluconeogenesis.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Of the 20 standard amino acids, nine (His, Ile, Leu, Lys, Met, Phe, Thr, Trp and Val) are called essential amino acids because the human body cannot synthesize them from other compounds at the level needed for normal growth, so they must be obtained from food.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In addition, cysteine, tyrosine, and arginine are considered semiessential amino acids, and taurine a semi-essential aminosulfonic acid in children.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Some amino acids are conditionally essential for certain ages or medical conditions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Essential amino acids may also vary from species to species.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The metabolic pathways that synthesize these monomers are not fully developed.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to animal feed because some of the components of these feeds, such as soybeans, have low levels of some of the essential amino acids, especially of lysine, methionine, threonine, and tryptophan.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Likewise amino acids are used to chelate metal cations in order to improve the absorption of minerals from feed supplements.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The food industry is a major consumer of amino acids, especially glutamic acid, which is used as a flavor enhancer, and aspartame (aspartylphenylalanine 1-methyl ester), which is used as an artificial sweetener.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to food by manufacturers to alleviate symptoms of mineral deficiencies, such as anemia, by improving mineral absorption and reducing negative side effects from inorganic mineral supplementation.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are low-cost feedstocks used in chiral pool synthesis as enantiomerically pure building blocks.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are used in the synthesis of some cosmetics.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The chelating ability of amino acids is sometimes used in fertilizers to facilitate the delivery of minerals to plants in order to correct mineral deficiencies, such as iron chlorosis.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] These fertilizers are also used to prevent deficiencies from occurring and to improve the overall health of the plants.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids have been considered as components of biodegradable polymers, which have applications as environmentally friendly packaging and in medicine in drug delivery and the construction of prosthetic implants.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] An interesting example of such materials is polyaspartate, a water-soluble biodegradable polymer that may have applications in disposable diapers and agriculture.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Due to its solubility and ability to chelate metal ions, polyaspartate is also being used as a biodegradable antiscaling agent and a corrosion inhibitor.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The commercial production of amino acids usually relies on mutant bacteria that overproduce individual amino acids using glucose as a carbon source.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Some amino acids are produced by enzymatic conversions of synthetic intermediates.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] 2-Aminothiazoline-4-carboxylic acid is an intermediate in one industrial synthesis of L-cysteine for example.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Aspartic acid is produced by the addition of ammonia to fumarate using a lyase.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In plants, nitrogen is first assimilated into organic compounds in the form of glutamate, formed from alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia in the mitochondrion.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] For other amino acids, plants use transaminases to move the amino group from glutamate to another alpha-keto acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, aspartate aminotransferase converts glutamate and oxaloacetate to alpha-ketoglutarate and aspartate.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Other organisms use transaminases for amino acid synthesis, too.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Nonstandard amino acids are usually formed through modifications to standard amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, homocysteine is formed through the transsulfuration pathway or by the demethylation of methionine via the intermediate metabolite *S*-adenosylmethionine, while hydroxyproline is made by a post translational modification of proline.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Microorganisms and plants synthesize many uncommon amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, some microbes make 2-aminoisobutyric acid and lanthionine, which is a sulfide-bridged derivative of alanine.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Both of these amino acids are found in peptidic lantibiotics such as alamethicin.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] However, in plants, 1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic acid is a small disubstituted cyclic amino acid that is an intermediate in the production of the plant hormone ethylene.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The formation of amino acids and peptides is assumed to have preceded and perhaps induced the emergence of life on earth.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids can form from simple precursors under various conditions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Surface-based chemical metabolism of amino acids and very small compounds may have led to the build-up of amino acids, coenzymes and phosphate-based small carbon molecules.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids and similar building blocks could have been elaborated into proto-peptides, with peptides being considered key players in the origin of life.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In the famous Urey-Miller experiment, the passage of an electric arc through a mixture of methane, hydrogen, and ammonia produces a large number of amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Several hypotheses invoke the Strecker synthesis whereby hydrogen cyanide, simple aldehydes, ammonia, and water produce amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] According to a review, amino acids, and even peptides, "turn up fairly regularly in the various experimental broths that have been allowed to be cooked from simple chemicals.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] This is because nucleotides are far more difficult to synthesize chemically than amino acids." For a chronological order, it suggests that there must have been a 'protein world' or at least a 'polypeptide world', possibly later followed by the 'RNA world' and the 'DNA world'.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Codon–amino acids mappings may be the biological information system at the primordial origin of life on Earth.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] While amino acids and consequently simple peptides must have formed under different experimentally probed geochemical scenarios, the transition from an abiotic world to the first life forms is to a large extent still unresolved.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids undergo the reactions expected of the constituent functional groups.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] As both the amine and carboxylic acid groups of amino acids can react to form amide bonds, one amino acid molecule can react with another and become joined through an amide linkage.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] This polymerization of amino acids is what creates proteins.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] This condensation reaction yields the newly formed peptide bond and a molecule of water.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In cells, this reaction does not occur directly; instead, the amino acid is first activated by attachment to a transfer RNA molecule through an ester bond.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is produced in an ATP-dependent reaction carried out by an aminoacyl tRNA synthetase.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is then a substrate for the ribosome, which catalyzes the attack of the amino group of the elongating protein chain on the ester bond.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] As a result of this mechanism, all proteins made by ribosomes are synthesized starting at their *N*-terminus and moving toward their *C*-terminus.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] However, not all peptide bonds are formed in this way.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In a few cases, peptides are synthesized by specific enzymes.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, the tripeptide glutathione is an essential part of the defenses of cells against oxidative stress.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] This peptide is synthesized in two steps from free amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In the first step, gamma-glutamylcysteine synthetase condenses cysteine and glutamate through a peptide bond formed between the side chain carboxyl of the glutamate (the gamma carbon of this side chain) and the amino group of the cysteine.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] This dipeptide is then condensed with glycine by glutathione synthetase to form glutathione.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In chemistry, peptides are synthesized by a variety of reactions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] One of the most-used in solid-phase peptide synthesis uses the aromatic oxime derivatives of amino acids as activated units.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] These are added in sequence onto the growing peptide chain, which is attached to a solid resin support.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Libraries of peptides are used in drug discovery through high-throughput screening.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The combination of functional groups allow amino acids to be effective polydentate ligands for metal–amino acid chelates.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The side chains of amino acids can also undergo posttranslational chemical reactions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Degradation of an amino acid often begins with transamination, in which its amino group is transferred to α-ketoglutarate, forming glutamate.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] This process involves transaminases, often the same enzymes used in amino acid synthesis.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] In many vertebrates, the amino group is subsequently released as ammonia and converted to urea via the urea cycle for excretion.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] However, amino acid degradation can result in uric acid or ammonia instead, depending on the organism.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] For example, serine dehydratase converts serine directly to pyruvate and ammonia.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] Amino acids are bidentate ligands, forming transition metal amino acid complexes.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The total nitrogen content of organic matter is mainly formed by the amino groups in proteins.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] The total Kjeldahl nitrogen (TKN) is a measure of nitrogen widely used in the analysis of (waste) water, soil, food, feed and organic matter in general.
[src:essential-amino-acid/amino-acid] As the name suggests, the Kjeldahl method is applied.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] A wide range of other species, such as horse, water buffalo, llama, rabbit, and guinea pig, are used as livestock in some parts of the world.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Insect farming, as well as aquaculture of fish, molluscs, and crustaceans, is widespread.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Modern animal husbandry relies on production systems adapted to the available land.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Subsistence farming is being superseded by intensive animal farming in the more developed parts of the world, where, for example, beef cattle are kept in high-density feedlots, and thousands of chickens may be raised in broiler houses or batteries.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] On poorer soil, such as in uplands, animals are often kept more extensively and may be allowed to roam widely, foraging for themselves.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Animal agriculture at modern scale drives climate change, ocean acidification, and biodiversity loss.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Most livestock are herbivores, except (among the most commonly-kept species) for pigs and chickens, which are omnivores.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Ruminants like cattle and sheep are adapted to feed on grass; they can forage outdoors or may be fed entirely or in part on rations richer in energy and protein, such as pelleted cereals.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Pigs and poultry cannot digest the cellulose in forage and require other high-protein foods.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Farmers and ranchers who raise livestock are considered to practice *animal husbandry*.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The domestication of livestock was driven by the need to have food on hand when hunting was unproductive.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The desirable characteristics of a domestic animal are that it should be useful to the domesticator, should be able to thrive in their company, should breed freely, and be easy to tend.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Domestication was not a single event, but a process repeated at various periods in different places.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Sheep and goats were the animals that accompanied the nomads in the Middle East, while cattle and pigs were associated with more settled communities.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The first wild animal to be domesticated was the dog.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Half-wild dogs, perhaps starting with young individuals, may have been tolerated as scavengers and killers of vermin, and, being naturally pack hunters, were predisposed to become part of the human pack and join in the hunt.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Prey animals, sheep, goats, pigs, and cattle, were progressively domesticated early in the history of agriculture.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Pigs were domesticated in the Near East between 8,500 and 8000 BC, sheep and goats in or near the Fertile Crescent about 8,500 BC, and cattle from wild aurochs in the areas of modern Turkey and Pakistan around 8,500 BC.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] A cow was a great advantage to a villager as she produced more milk than her calf needed, and her strength could be put to use as a working animal, pulling a plough to increase production of crops, and drawing a sledge, and later a cart, to bring the produce home from the field.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Draught animals were first used about 4,000 BC in the Middle East, increasing agricultural production immeasurably.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In southern Asia, the elephant was domesticated by 6,000 BC.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Fossilised chicken bones dated to 5040 BC have been found in northeastern China, far from where their wild ancestors lived in the jungles of tropical Asia, but archaeologists believe that the original purpose of domestication was for the sport of cockfighting.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Meanwhile, in South America, the llama and the alpaca had been domesticated, probably before 3,000 BC, as beasts of burden and for their wool.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Neither was strong enough to pull a plough, which limited the development of agriculture in the New World.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Horses occur naturally on the steppes of Central Asia, and their domestication began around 3,000 BC in the Black Sea and Caspian Sea region.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Although horses were originally seen as a source of meat, their use as pack animals and for riding followed.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Around the same time, the wild ass was being tamed in Egypt.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Camels were domesticated soon after this, with the Bactrian camel in Mongolia and the Arabian camel becoming beasts of burden.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] By 1000 BC, caravans of Arabian camels were linking India with Mesopotamia and the Mediterranean.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In ancient Egypt, cattle were the most important livestock, and sheep, goats, and pigs were also kept; poultry including ducks, geese, and pigeons were captured in nets and bred on farms, where they were force-fed with dough to fatten them.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The Nile provided a plentiful source of fish.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Honey bees were domesticated from at least the Old Kingdom, providing both honey and wax.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In ancient Rome, all the livestock known in ancient Egypt were available.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In addition, rabbits were domesticated for food by the first century BC.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] To help flush them out from their burrows, the polecat was domesticated as the ferret, its use described by Pliny the Elder.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In northern Europe, agriculture, including animal husbandry, declined after the collapse of the Roman Empire.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Some aspects, such as the herding of animals, continued throughout the period.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] By the 11th century, the economy had recovered, and the countryside was again productive.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Woodland for [feeding] 70 pigs." The improvements of animal husbandry in the medieval period in Europe went hand in hand with other developments.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Improvements to the plough allowed the soil to be tilled to a greater depth.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Horses took over from oxen as the main providers of traction, new ideas on crop rotation were developed, and the growing of crops for winter fodder gained ground.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Peas, beans, and vetches became common; they increased soil fertility through nitrogen fixation, allowing more livestock to be kept.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The exploration and colonisation of North and South America resulted in the introduction of crops such as maize, potatoes, sweet potatoes, and manioc into Europe.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] At the same time, the principal Old World livestock – cattle, horses, sheep, and goats – were introduced into the New World for the first time along with wheat, barley, rice, and turnips.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Selective breeding for desired traits was established as a scientific practice by Robert Bakewell during the British Agricultural Revolution in the 18th century.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] One of his most important breeding programs was with sheep.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Using native stock, he was able to quickly select for large, yet fine-boned sheep, with long, lustrous wool.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The Lincoln Longwool was improved by Bakewell, and, in turn, the Lincoln was used to develop the subsequent breed, the New (or Dishley) Leicester.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] It was hornless and had a square, meaty body with straight top lines.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] These sheep were exported widely and have contributed to numerous modern breeds.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Under his influence, English farmers began to breed cattle primarily for beef.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Long-horned heifers were crossed with the Westmoreland bull to create the Dishley Longhorn.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The semi-natural, unfertilised pastures formed by traditional agricultural methods in Europe were managed by grazing and mowing.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] As the ecological impact of this land management strategy is similar to that of natural disturbances such as grazing and wildfire, this agricultural system shares many beneficial characteristics with a natural habitat, including promoting biodiversity.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] This strategy is declining in Europe today due to intensified agriculture.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The mechanized and chemical methods used are causing biodiversity to decline.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Traditionally, animal husbandry was part of the subsistence farmer's way of life, producing not only the food needed by the family but also the fuel, fertiliser, clothing, transport, and draught power.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Killing the animal for food was a secondary consideration; wherever possible its products such as wool, eggs, milk and blood (by the Maasai) were harvested while the animal was still alive.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In the traditional system of transhumance, people and livestock moved seasonally between fixed summer and winter pastures; in montane regions the summer pasture was up in the mountains, the winter pasture in the valleys.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Animals can be kept extensively or intensively.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Extensive systems involve animals roaming at will, or under the supervision of a herdsman, often for their protection from predators.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Ranching in the Western United States involves large herds of cattle grazing widely over public and private lands.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Similar cattle stations are found in South America, Australia, and other places with large areas of land and low rainfall.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Ranching systems have been used for sheep, deer, ostrich, emu, llama and alpaca.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In the uplands of the United Kingdom, sheep are turned out on the fells in spring and graze the abundant mountain grasses untended, being brought to lower altitudes late in the year, with supplementary feeding being provided in winter.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In rural locations, pigs and poultry can obtain much of their nutrition from scavenging, and in African communities, hens may live for months without being fed, and still produce one or two eggs a week.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In between these two extremes are semi-intensive, often family-run farms where livestock graze outside for much of the year, silage or hay is made to cover the times of year when the grass stops growing, and fertiliser, feed, and other inputs are brought onto the farm from outside.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Animals used as livestock are predominantly herbivorous, the main exceptions being the pig and the chicken, which are omnivorous.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Herbivores can be divided into "concentrate selectors", which selectively feed on seeds, fruits, and highly nutritious young foliage; "grazers", which mainly feed on grass; and "intermediate feeders", which choose their diet from the full range of available plant material.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Cattle, sheep, goats, deer, and antelopes are ruminants; they digest food in two steps, chewing and swallowing in the normal way, and then regurgitating the semidigested cud to chew it again and thus extract the maximum possible food value.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The dietary needs of these animals are mostly met by eating grass.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Grasses grow from the base of the leaf-blade, enabling it to thrive even when heavily grazed or cut.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In many climates, grass growth is seasonal, for example, in the temperate summer or tropical rainy season, so some areas of the crop are set aside to be cut and preserved, either as hay (dried grass), or as silage (fermented grass).
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Other forage crops are also grown and many of these, as well as crop residues, can be ensiled to fill the gap in the nutritional needs of livestock in the lean season.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Extensively reared animals may subsist entirely on forage, but more intensively kept livestock will require energy and protein-rich foods in addition.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Energy is mainly derived from cereals and cereal by-products, fats and oils, and sugar-rich foods, while protein may come from fish or meat meal, milk products, legumes, and other plant foods, often the by-products of vegetable oil extraction.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Pigs and poultry are non-ruminants and are unable to digest the cellulose in grass and other forages, so they are fed entirely on cereals and other high-energy foodstuffs.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The ingredients for the animals' rations can be grown on the farm or bought as pelleted or cubed compound foodstuffs, specially formulated for different classes of livestock, their growth stages, and their specific nutritional requirements.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Vitamins and minerals are added to balance the diet.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Farmed fish are usually fed pelleted food.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The breeding of farm animals seldom occurs spontaneously but is managed by farmers to encourage traits considered desirable.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] These include hardiness, fertility, docility, mothering abilities, fast growth rates, low feed consumption per unit of growth, better body proportions, higher yields, and better fibre qualities.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Undesirable traits such as health defects and aggressiveness are selected against.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Selective breeding has been responsible for significant productivity increases.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] For example, in 2007, a typical broiler chicken at eight weeks old was 4.8 times as heavy as a bird of similar age in 1957, while in the thirty years to 2007, the average milk yield of a dairy cow in the United States nearly doubled.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Good husbandry, proper feeding, and hygiene are the main contributors to animal health on the farm, bringing economic benefits through maximised production.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] When, despite these precautions, animals still become sick, they are treated with veterinary medicines, by the farmer and the veterinarian.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In the European Union, when farmers treat their own animals, they are required to follow treatment guidelines and record the treatments given.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Animals are susceptible to many diseases and conditions that may affect their health.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Some, like classical swine fever and scrapie are specific to one type of stock, while others, like foot-and-mouth disease affect all cloven-hoofed animals.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Animals living under intensive conditions are prone to internal and external parasites; increasing numbers of sea lice are affecting farmed salmon in Scotland.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Reducing the parasite burdens of livestock results in increased productivity and profitability.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Where the condition is serious, governments impose regulations on imports and exports, the movement of stock, quarantine restrictions, and the reporting of suspected cases.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Vaccines are available against certain diseases, and antibiotics are widely used where appropriate.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] At one time, antibiotics were routinely added to certain compound foodstuffs to promote growth.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Still, this practice is now frowned on in many countries because of the risk that it may lead to antimicrobial resistance in livestock and in humans.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Governments are concerned with zoonoses, diseases that humans may acquire from animals.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Wild animal populations may harbour diseases that can affect domestic animals, which may acquire them as a result of insufficient biosecurity.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] An outbreak of Nipah virus in Malaysia in 1999 was traced back to pigs becoming ill after contact with fruit-eating flying foxes, their faeces and urine.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The pigs, in turn, passed the infection to humans.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Avian flu H5N1 is present in wild bird populations and can be carried large distances by migrating birds.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] This virus is easily transmissible to domestic poultry and to humans living in proximity to them.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Other infectious diseases affecting wild animals, farm animals and humans include rabies, leptospirosis, brucellosis, tuberculosis and trichinosis.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] There is no single universally agreed-upon definition of what species are considered livestock.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Widely recognized livestock types include cattle for beef and dairy, sheep, goats, pigs, and poultry.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Various other species are sometimes considered livestock, such as horses, while poultry birds are sometimes excluded.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In some parts of the world, livestock includes species such as buffalo, and the South American camelids, the alpaca and llama.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Some authorities use much broader definitions to include fish in aquaculture, micro-livestock such as rabbits and rodents like guinea pigs, as well as insects from honey bees to crickets raised for human consumption.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Animals are raised for a wide variety of products, principally meat, wool, milk, and eggs, but also including tallow, isinglass, and rennet.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Animals are also kept for more specialised purposes, such as to produce vaccines and antiserum (containing antibodies) for medical use.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Where fodder or other crops are grown alongside animals, manure can serve as a fertiliser, returning minerals and organic matter to the soil in a semi-closed organic system.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Although all mammals produce milk to nourish their young, cows are predominantly used worldwide to produce milk and milk products for human consumption.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Other animals used to a lesser extent for this purpose include sheep, goats, camels, buffaloes, yaks, reindeer, horses, and donkeys.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] All these animals have been domesticated over the centuries, bred for desirable characteristics such as fecundity, productivity, docility, and the ability to thrive under prevailing conditions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Whereas in the past cattle had multiple functions, modern dairy cow breeding has produced specialised Holstein Friesian-type animals that produce large quantities of milk economically.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Artificial insemination is widely available, allowing farmers to select for traits that suit their circumstances.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In many communities, milk production is only part of the purpose of keeping an animal, which may also be used as a beast of burden or to draw a plough, or for the production of fibre, meat and leather, with the dung being used for fuel or for the improvement of soil fertility.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Sheep and goats may be favoured for dairy production in climates and conditions that do not suit dairy cows.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Meat, mainly from farmed animals, is a major source of dietary protein and essential nutrients around the world, averaging about 8% of human energy intake.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The actual types eaten depend on local preferences, availability, cost, and other factors, with cattle, sheep, pigs, and goats being the main species involved.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Cattle generally produce a single offspring annually which takes more than a year to mature; sheep and goats often have twins and these are ready for slaughter in less than a year; pigs are more prolific, producing more than one litter of up to about 11 piglets each year.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Horses, donkeys, deer, buffalo, llamas, alpacas, guanacos and vicunas are farmed for meat in various regions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Some desirable traits of animals raised for meat include fecundity, hardiness, fast growth rate, ease of management, and high food conversion efficiency.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] About half of the world's meat is produced from animals grazing on open ranges or enclosed pastures; the other half is produced intensively in various factory-farming systems.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] These are mostly cows, pigs, or poultry, and are often reared indoors at high densities.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Poultry kept for their eggs and meat include chickens, turkeys, geese, and ducks.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The great majority of laying birds used for egg production are chickens.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The battery cages are arranged in long rows across multiple tiers, with external feeders, drinkers, and egg-collection facilities.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] This is the most labour-saving and economical method of egg production.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Still, it has been criticised on animal-welfare grounds because the birds are unable to exhibit their normal behaviours.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In the developed world, the majority of poultry reared for meat is raised indoors in large sheds, with automated equipment and environmentally controlled conditions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Chickens raised in this way are known as broilers, and genetic improvements have enabled them to reach slaughter weight within six or seven weeks of hatching.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Newly hatched chicks are confined to a small area and provided with supplementary heating.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Litter on the floor absorbs droppings, and the area it occupies expands as they grow.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Feed and water are supplied automatically, and the lighting is controlled.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The birds may be harvested on several occasions, or the entire shed may be cleared at once.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] A similar rearing system is usually used for turkeys, which are less hardy than chickens, take longer to reach maturity, and are often moved to separate fattening units to finish.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Ducks are particularly popular in Asia and Australia and can be killed at seven weeks under commercial conditions.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Aquaculture has been defined as "the farming of aquatic organisms, including fish, molluscs, crustaceans, and aquatic plants, and implies some form of intervention in the rearing process to enhance production, such as regular stocking, feeding, protection from predators, etc.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Farming also implies individual or corporate ownership of the stock being cultivated." In practice, it can take place in the sea or in freshwater, and be extensive or intensive.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Whole bays, lakes, or ponds may be devoted to aquaculture, or the farmed animal may be retained in cages (fish), artificial reefs, racks, or strings (shellfish).
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Fish and prawns can be cultivated in rice paddies, either arriving naturally or being introduced, and both crops can be harvested together.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Fish hatcheries provide larval and juvenile fish, crustaceans, and shellfish for use in aquaculture systems.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] When large enough, these are transferred to growing-on tanks and sold to fish farms for harvest.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Some species that are commonly raised in hatcheries include shrimps, prawns, salmon, tilapia, oysters and scallops.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Similar facilities can be used to raise species with conservation needs for release into the wild, or game fish for restocking waterways.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Important aspects of husbandry at these early stages include selection of breeding stock, control of water quality, and nutrition.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In the wild, there is a high mortality rate at the nursery stage; farmers seek to minimise it while maximising growth rates.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Bees have been kept in hives since at least the First Dynasty of Egypt, five thousand years ago, and man had been harvesting honey from the wild long before that.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Fixed-comb hives are used in many parts of the world and are made from locally available materials.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In more advanced economies, where modern strains of domestic bee have been selected for docility and productiveness, various designs of hive are used which enable the combs to be removed for processing and extraction of honey.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Quite apart from the honey and wax they produce, honey bees are important pollinators of crops and wild plants, and in many places hives are transported around the countryside to assist in pollination.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Sericulture, the rearing of silkworms, was first adopted by the Chinese during the Shang dynasty.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The only species farmed commercially is the domesticated silkmoth.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] When it spins its cocoon, each larva produces an exceedingly long, slender thread of silk.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The larvae feed on mulberry leaves, and in Europe, only one generation is typically raised each year because mulberry is a deciduous tree.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In China, Korea, and Japan, however, two generations are normal, and in the tropics, multiple generations are expected.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Most silk production occurs in the Far East, with synthetic diets used to rear silkworms in Japan.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Insects form part of the human diet in many cultures.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In Thailand, crickets are farmed for this purpose in the north of the country, and palm weevil larvae in the south.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The crickets are kept in pens, boxes, or drawers and fed on commercial pelleted poultry food, while the palm weevil larvae live on cabbage palm and sago palm trees, which limits their production to areas where these trees grow.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Another delicacy of this region is the bamboo caterpillar, and the best rearing and harvesting techniques in semi-natural habitats are being studied.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Animal husbandry has a significant impact on the world environment.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Both production and consumption of animal products have increased rapidly.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Since 1950, meat production has tripled, dairy production has doubled, and egg production has increased almost fourfold.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Meanwhile, meat consumption has nearly doubled worldwide.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Developing countries had a surge in meat consumption, particularly of monogastric livestock.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Animal husbandry drives climate change, ocean acidification, and biodiversity loss, and kills 60 billion animals annually.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] It uses between 20 and 33% of the world's fresh water, Livestock, and the production of feed for them, occupy about a third of the Earth's ice-free land.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Livestock production contributes to species extinction, desertification, and habitat destruction. and is the primary driver of the Holocene extinction.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Some 70% of the agricultural land and 30% of Earth's land surface is involved directly or indirectly in animal husbandry.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Habitat is destroyed by clearing forests and converting land to grow feed crops and for grazing, while predators and herbivores are frequently targeted because of a perceived threat to livestock profits; for example, animal husbandry causes up to 91% of the deforestation in the Amazon region.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] In addition, livestock produce greenhouse gases.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Cows produce some 570 million cubic metres of methane per day, that accounts for 35 to 40% of the overall methane emissions of the planet.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Further, livestock production is responsible for 65% of all human-related emissions of nitrous oxide.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Since the 18th century, people have become increasingly concerned about the welfare of farm animals.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Possible measures of welfare include longevity, behavior, physiology, reproduction, freedom from disease, and freedom from immunosuppression.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] An opposing view is that animals have rights, should not be regarded as property, are not necessary to use, and should never be used by humans.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Live export of animals has risen to meet increased global demand for livestock, such as in the Middle East.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Animal rights activists have objected to the long-distance transport of animals; one result was the banning of live exports from New Zealand in 2003.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Since the 18th century, the farmer John Bull has represented English national identity, first in John Arbuthnot's political satires, and soon afterwards in cartoons by James Gillray and others, including John Tenniel.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] He likes food, beer, dogs, horses, and country sports; he is practical, down-to-earth, and anti-intellectual.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Farm animals are widespread in children's books and songs; the reality of animal husbandry is often distorted, softened, or idealized, giving children an almost entirely fictitious account of farm life.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The books often depict happy animals free to roam in attractive countryside, a picture completely at odds with the realities of the impersonal, mechanized activities involved in modern intensive farming.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Pigs, for example, appear in several of Beatrix Potter's "little books", as Piglet in A.A.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Milne's Winnie the Pooh stories, and somewhat more darkly (with a hint of animals going to slaughter) as Babe in Dick King-Smith's *The Sheep-Pig*, and as Wilbur in E.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Pigs tend to be "bearers of cheerfulness, good humour and innocence".
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Many of these books are completely anthropomorphic, dressing farm animals in clothes and having them walk on two legs, live in houses, and perform human activities.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] The children's song "Old MacDonald Had a Farm" describes a farmer named MacDonald and the various animals he keeps, celebrating the noises they each make.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Many urban children experience animal husbandry for the first time at a petting farm; in Britain, some five million people a year visit a farm of some kind.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] This presents some risk of infection, especially if children handle animals and then fail to wash their hands; a strain of *E. coli* infected 93 people who had visited a British interactive farm in an outbreak in 2009.
[src:essential-amino-acid/animal-husbandry] Historic farms such as those in the United States offer farmstays and "a carefully curated version of farming to those willing to pay for it", sometimes giving visitors a romanticised image of a pastoral idyll from an unspecified time in the pre-industrial past.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] An **essential amino acid**, or **indispensable amino acid**, is an amino acid that cannot be synthesized from scratch by the organism fast enough to supply its demand, and must therefore come from the diet.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Of the 21 amino acids common to all life forms, the nine amino acids humans cannot synthesize are valine, isoleucine, leucine, methionine, phenylalanine, tryptophan, threonine, histidine, and lysine.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Six other amino acids are considered **conditionally essential** in the human diet, meaning their synthesis can be limited under special pathophysiological conditions, such as prematurity in the infant or individuals in severe catabolic distress.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] These six are arginine, cysteine, glycine, glutamine, proline, and tyrosine.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Six amino acids are non-essential (**dispensable**) in humans, meaning they can be synthesized in sufficient quantities in the body.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] These six are alanine, aspartic acid, asparagine, glutamic acid, serine, and selenocysteine (considered the 21st amino acid).
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Pyrrolysine (considered the 22nd amino acid), which is proteinogenic only in certain microorganisms, is not used by and therefore non-essential for most organisms, including humans.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The **limiting amino acid** is the essential amino acid which is furthest from meeting nutritional requirements.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] This concept is important when determining the selection, number, and amount of foods to consume: Even when total protein and all other essential amino acids are satisfied, if the limiting amino acid is not satisfied, then the meal is considered to be nutritionally limited by that amino acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] (*) Pyrrolysine, sometimes considered the "22nd amino acid", is not used by the human body.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Of the twenty amino acids common to all life forms (not counting selenocysteine), humans cannot synthesize nine: histidine, isoleucine, leucine, lysine, methionine, phenylalanine, threonine, tryptophan and valine.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] For example, enough arginine is synthesized by the urea cycle to meet the needs of an adult but perhaps not those of a growing child.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Amino acids that must be obtained from the diet are called **essential amino acids**.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Eukaryotes can synthesize some of the amino acids from other substrates.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Consequently, only a subset of the amino acids used in protein synthesis are essential nutrients.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Nonessential amino acids are produced in the body.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The pathways for the synthesis of nonessential amino acids come from basic metabolic pathways.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Glutamate dehydrogenase catalyzes the reductive amination of α-ketoglutarate to glutamate.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] A transamination reaction takes place in the synthesis of most amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] At this step, the chirality of the amino acid is established.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Alanine and aspartate are synthesized by the transamination of pyruvate and oxaloacetate, respectively.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Glutamine is synthesized from NH4+ and glutamate, and asparagine is synthesized similarly.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Proline and arginine are both derived from glutamate.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Serine, formed from 3-phosphoglycerate, which comes from glycolysis, is the precursor of glycine and cysteine.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Tyrosine is synthesized by the hydroxylation of phenylalanine, which is an essential amino acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Estimating the daily requirement for the indispensable amino acids has proven to be difficult; these numbers have undergone considerable revision over the last 20 years.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The following table lists the recommended daily amounts currently in use for essential amino acids in **adult humans** (unless specified otherwise), together with their standard one-letter abbreviations.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The recommended daily intakes for children aged three years and older is 10% to 20% higher than adult levels and those for infants can be as much as 150% higher in the first year of life.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Cysteine (or sulfur-containing amino acids), tyrosine (or aromatic amino acids), and arginine are always required by infants and growing children.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Methionine and cysteine are grouped together because one of them can be synthesized from the other using the enzyme methionine *S*-methyltransferase and the catalyst methionine synthase.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Phenylalanine and tyrosine are grouped together because tyrosine can be synthesized from phenylalanine using the enzyme phenylalanine hydroxylase.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Historically, amino acid requirements were determined by calculating the balance between dietary nitrogen intake and nitrogen excreted in the liquid and solid wastes, because proteins represent the largest nitrogen content in a body.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] A positive balance occurs when more nitrogen is consumed than is excreted, which indicates that some of the nitrogen is being used by the body to build proteins.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] A negative nitrogen balance occurs when more nitrogen is excreted than is consumed, which indicates that there is insufficient intake for the body to maintain its health.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Graduate students at the University of Illinois were fed an artificial diet so that there was a slightly positive nitrogen balance.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Then one amino acid was omitted and the nitrogen balance recorded.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] If a positive balance continued, then that amino acid was deemed not essential.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] If a negative balance occurred, then that amino acid was slowly restored until a slightly positive nitrogen balance stabilized and the minimum amount recorded.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] A similar method was used to determine the protein content of foods.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Test subjects were fed a diet containing no protein and the nitrogen losses recorded.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] During the first week or more there is a rapid loss of labile proteins.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Once the nitrogen losses stabilize, this baseline is determined to be the minimum required for maintenance.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Then the test subjects were fed a measured amount of the food being tested.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The difference between the nitrogen in that food and the nitrogen losses above baseline was the amount the body retained to rebuild proteins.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The amount of nitrogen retained divided by the total nitrogen intake is called net protein utilization.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The amount of nitrogen retained divided by the (nitrogen intake minus nitrogen loss above baseline) is called biological value and is usually given as a percentage.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Modern techniques make use of ion exchange chromatography to determine the actual amino acid content of foods.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The USDA used this technique in their own labs to determine the content of 7793 foods across 28 categories.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The USDA published the final database in 2018 to the public.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The limiting amino acid depends on the human requirements and there are currently two sets of human requirements from authoritative sources: one published by WHO and the other published by USDA.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Various attempts have been made to express the "quality" or "value" of various kinds of protein.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Measures include the biological value, net protein utilization, protein efficiency ratio, protein digestibility corrected amino acid score and the complete proteins concept.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] These concepts are important in the livestock industry, because the relative lack of one or more of the essential amino acids in animal feeds would have a limiting effect on growth and thus on feed conversion ratio.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Thus, various feedstuffs may be fed in combination to increase net protein utilization, or a supplement of an individual amino acid (methionine, lysine, threonine, or tryptophan) can be added to the feed.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Protein content in foods is often measured in protein per serving rather than protein per calorie.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] For instance, the USDA lists 6 grams of protein per large whole egg (a 50-gram serving) rather than 84 mg of protein per calorie (71 calories total).
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] For comparison, there are 2.8 grams of protein in a serving of raw broccoli (100 grams) or 82 mg of protein per calorie (34 calories total), or the Daily Value of 47.67g of protein after eating 1,690g of raw broccoli a day at 574 cal.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] An egg contains 12.5g of protein per 100g, but 4 mg more protein per calorie, or the protein DV after 381g of egg, which is 545 cal.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The ratio of essential amino acids (the quality of protein) is not taken into account, one would actually need to eat more than 3 kg of broccoli a day to have a healthy protein profile, and almost 6 kg to get enough calories.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] It is recommended that adult humans obtain between 10–35% of their 2000 calories a day as protein.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Scientists had known since the early 20th century that rats could not survive on a diet whose only protein source was zein, which comes from maize (corn), but recovered if they were fed casein from cow's milk.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] This led William Cumming Rose to the discovery of the essential amino acid threonine.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Through manipulation of rodent diets, Rose was able to show that ten amino acids are essential for rats: lysine, tryptophan, histidine, phenylalanine, leucine, isoleucine, methionine, valine, and arginine, in addition to threonine.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Rose's later work showed that eight amino acids are essential for adult human beings, with histidine also being essential for infants.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Longer-term studies established histidine as also essential for adult humans.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The distinction between essential and non-essential amino acids is somewhat unclear, as some amino acids can be produced from others.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The sulfur-containing amino acids, methionine and homocysteine, can be converted into each other but neither can be synthesized *de novo* in humans.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Likewise, cysteine can be made from homocysteine but cannot be synthesized on its own.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] So, for convenience, sulfur-containing amino acids are sometimes considered a single pool of nutritionally equivalent amino acids as are the aromatic amino acid pair, phenylalanine and tyrosine.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Likewise arginine, ornithine, and citrulline, which are interconvertible by the urea cycle, are considered a single group.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] If one of the essential amino acids is not available in the required quantities, protein synthesis will be inhibited, irrespective of the availability of the other amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The physical signs of protein deficiency include edema, failure to thrive in infants and children, poor musculature, dull skin, and thin and fragile hair.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Biochemical changes reflecting protein deficiency include low serum albumin and low serum transferrin.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The amino acids that are essential in the human diet were established in a series of experiments led by William Cumming Rose.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The experiments involved elemental diets to healthy male graduate students.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] These diets consisted of corn starch, sucrose, butterfat without protein, corn oil, inorganic salts, the known vitamins, a large brown "candy" made of liver extract flavored with peppermint oil (to supply any unknown vitamins), and mixtures of highly purified individual amino acids.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] The main outcome measure was nitrogen balance.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Rose noted that the symptoms of nervousness, exhaustion, and dizziness were encountered to a greater or lesser extent whenever human subjects were deprived of an essential amino acid.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Essential amino acid deficiency should be distinguished from protein-energy malnutrition, which can manifest as marasmus or kwashiorkor.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Kwashiorkor was once attributed to pure protein deficiency in individuals who were consuming enough calories ("sugar baby syndrome").
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] However, this theory has been challenged by the finding that there is no difference in the diets of children developing marasmus as opposed to kwashiorkor.
[src:essential-amino-acid/essential-amino-acid] Still, for instance in Dietary Reference Intakes (DRI) maintained by the USDA, lack of one or more of the essential amino acids is described as protein-energy malnutrition.
